@@yThe Great Pyramid@@N

@@eScholars call it the Ladder of Noon, for at a distance its terraces catch the
sun and pour light across the dunes like molten brass. But the public story of
a jeweled tomb is only the surface of a deeper truth.@@N

@@WThe Solar Court of the Undivided Disk raised this monument as three institutions
in one body of stone: a public machine of kingship, a hidden machine of soul
adjudication, and a sealed machine of cosmic containment. At its deepest core
lies the Black Sun Shard, a fragment of anti-light that consumes names,
certainties, and memory itself.@@N

@@ySix construction eras layered the pyramid into the political fossil it is today.
Processional causeways gave way to priestly ink vaults, then catacomb labor lines,
tribunal halls, militarized war sancta, and finally the forbidden apex seals.@@N

@@rPharaoh Ramesses-of-the-First-Binding accepted partial soul-binding to keep the
Shard dormant after a catastrophic breach. He did not become immortal in triumph;
he became unfinished in service.@@N

@@eThe Ushabti guardians still walk its corridors, carved from quarry stone and
given genuine will so they may exercise genuine judgment. The Jackal Tribunal
weighs the dead in three sentence classes: Interment, Service, and Correction.
The third class was used to rewrite entire noble bloodlines for political
continuity.@@N

@@dWhen the court collapsed, the pyramid sealed itself via automatic protocols and
bloodline locks that no longer had living custodians. For generations it was
considered cursed but static. Now tomb extraction crews, cult revivals, and
desert arcane storms have broken those seals.@@N

@@rThe pyramid still functions. Its ghosts defend particular eras, doctrines, and
forged histories. Adventurers do not enter a simple dungeon. They enter a civil
war preserved in ritual amber.@@N
